./sdp/logs/Verify_T-005_20260408T223256Z_1775690314.log:2753:+**PASS WITH NOTES.** Core happy path and error-output detection (`success = not output.startswith("[")`) are tested. The healer path is exercised by a `resolved=False` stub that confirms no crash. One minor gap: no dedicated test for the case where `_invoke_ollama` raises an unexpected exception (which falls through to the outer `except Exception` block at line 964). This edge case is already covered by the generic daemon fallback tests and is not specific to T-004.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-005_20260408T223256Z_1775690314.log:2755:+The `task_category` parameter of `_invoke_ollama` is not forwarded from `run_agent` (it defaults to `None`, which triggers category detection from `task_label`). This is intentional and consistent with T-003's design. No gap.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-005_20260408T223256Z_1775690314.log:2761:+**PASS.** The ollama branch mirrors the structure of the subprocess path: spinner start → pet start → do work → compute duration → pet end → schedule idle → observatory record → healer if failure → return. The duplicate `if/elif` failure-handling blocks (lines 820–839) replicate the same pattern used at lines 920–939 for subprocess agents — minor code smell, consistent with existing style. The `finally` block (semaphore release, `semaphore_released` event) is shared with all paths.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-005_20260408T223256Z_1775690314.log:2767:+**PASS.** The ollama branch makes no subprocess calls. `_invoke_ollama` uses `urllib.request` with a JSON-encoded payload; user prompt is placed in a JSON field (not interpolated into a shell command or URL path). No secrets are logged. No new attack surface introduced.
